'''Al Meethaq''' ('''Ø¬ÙØ¹ÙØ© ÙÙØ«Ø§Ù Ø§ÙØ¹ÙÙ Ø§ÙÙØ·ÙÙ'''), or the ''''National Action Charter Society'''', is a liberal political party in [[Bahrain]].

It won no seats in the [[Bahraini parliamentary election, 2002|2002]] or [[Bahraini parliamentary election, 2006|2006]] general elections. Sixteen of its members were appointed by the [[King of Bahrain]] in 2002 to the wholly appointed [[Consultative Council of Bahrain]] which co-legislates with the elected [[Council of Representatives of Bahrain]].<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=10&categ_id=5&article_id=8120 Under the searing Bahrain sun, liberals with few illusions], [[Daily Star (Lebanon)]], 7 September 2004</ref>

With other liberal groups al Meethaq has established the [[Al Muntada]] activist group which campaigns for personal freedoms. <ref>[http://search.gulfnews.com/articles/05/11/20/193638.html Bahrain Forum to campaign for personal freedoms], [[Gulf News]], 20 November 2005</ref>

The party's leader is Ahmad Juma, who is culture editor of the newspaper, [[Al Ayam (Bahrain)|Al Ayam]].

